
LDAP stands for Lightweight Directory Access Protocol.
It is used to access and manage directory information, like:
•	Usernames
•	Passwords
•	Email addresses
•	Organizational data


Example LDAP query: (&(uid=admin)(password=123456))


This means:
•	Find user where uid = admin
•	AND password = 123456


LDAP Injection occurs when user input is not properly sanitized and gets inserted directly into an LDAP query.


If attacker enters: username: admin)(&)
                                 password: anything
The query becomes: (&(uid=admin)(&)(password=anything))
This may bypass authentication.


